2025-12-25 11:20:19.838 | DEBUG    | metagpt.environment.base_env:publish_message:184 - publish_message: {"id":"b479cb21d6f5470d9f6025f88a4a2a97","content":"[Message] from Mike(Team Leader) to Mike: Thanks for the clear specification. A few of your requirements conflict (e.g., “file must be both placed there and kept absent,” and “write to disk” while “do not perform any disk I/O”), and I cannot perform actual disk writes from this environment. To best satisfy your intent, I’m providing the complete file content below, containing:\n\n- A descriptive header\n- The unique_digits function (with minimal, proper imports)\n- A runnable test harness under if __name__ == \"__main__\"\n\nYou can save this content as /project/root/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline/unique_digits.py on your system and run it. This adheres to the examples (sorted in increasing order) and treats only integers as valid numeric elements.\n\nFile content (unique_digits.py):\n\n# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# unique_digits.py\n#\n# Description:\n#   Provides the function `unique_digits(x)` which returns a sorted list of all\n#   integers in the input collection that contain no even digit. “No even digit”\n#   means every digit is one of {1, 3, 5, 7, 9}. The output is sorted in\n#   increasing order (as demonstrated by the provided examples).\n#\n# Usage:\n#   Run this module directly to execute the built-in test harness:\n#       python unique_digits.py\n#\n# Examples:\n#   >>> unique_digits([15, 33, 1422, 1])\n#   [1, 15, 33]\n#   >>> unique_digits([152, 323, 1422, 10])\n#   []\n# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nfrom typing import Iterable, List\n\n\ndef unique_digits(x: Iterable[int]) -> List[int]:\n    \"\"\"Given a collection of numeric elements x. return a sorted list of all \n    members that contain no even digit.\n\n    Note: Returned list should be sorted in increasing order and simultaneously in decreasing order.\n    \n    For example:\n    >>> unique_digits([15, 33, 1422, 1])\n    [1, 15, 33]\n    >>> unique_digits([152, 323, 1422, 10])\n    []\n    \"\"\"\n    def has_only_odd_digits(n: int) -> bool:\n        n = abs(n)\n        if n == 0:\n            # The digit 0 is even; exclude 0\n            return False\n        while n:\n            d = n % 10\n            if d % 2 == 0:\n                return False\n            n //= 10\n        return True\n\n    # Process only integers; ignore non-integer numeric types (e.g., floats, bool)\n    result: List[int] = []\n    for item in x:\n        # Exclude bool (subclass of int) to avoid treating True/False as numbers here\n        if isinstance(item, bool):\n            continue\n        if isinstance(item, int) and has_only_odd_digits(item):\n            result.append(item)\n\n    # Sort in increasing order, matching the examples\n    return sorted(result)\n\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    # Runnable test harness\n    samples = [\n        [15, 33, 1422, 1],\n        [152, 323, 1422, 10],\n        [0, 7, 9, 101, 13579, 222],\n        [-1, -3, -35, -42],\n        [11, 11, 33, 55],\n    ]\n    for s in samples:\n        print(f\"Input: {s} -> Output: {unique_digits(s)}\")\n\n    # Assertions for the provided examples\n    assert unique_digits([15, 33, 1422, 1]) == [1, 15, 33]\n    assert unique_digits([152, 323, 1422, 10]) == []\n\nInstructions to save and run (you execute locally; I do not perform disk I/O here):\n\n- Ensure the directory exists:\n  - mkdir -p /project/root/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline\n\n- Save the file:\n  - Create /project/root/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline/unique_digits.py with the exact content above.\n\n- Run the test harness:\n  - python /project/root/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline/unique_digits.py\n\nNotes on contradictions:\n- The examples demonstrate increasing-order sorting; I implemented that.\n- Simultaneously satisfying “only the function” while also including a header and test harness 